The `ctx` is `AppContext` which defaults to `DefaultAppContext` (which is `{}`). We can use middleware to set `ctx.db = env.DB`.

But actually, the simplest approach is to just wrap the `fetch` method and use a module-level variable to store the current `env.DB`:

```typescript
let currentDb: D1Database | null = null;

const app = defineApp([...]);

const originalFetch = app.fetch;
app.fetch = async (request, env, cf) => {
    currentDb = env.DB;
    try {
        return await originalFetch.call(app, request, env, cf);
    } finally {
        currentDb = null;
    }
};

export default app;
```

But this is not thread-safe. In Workers, each request runs in its own isolate, but within a single isolate, multiple requests might be processed concurrently.

A better approach is to use AsyncLocalStorage to store `env.DB`:

```typescript
import { AsyncLocalStorage } from 'async_hooks';

const dbStorage = new AsyncLocalStorage<D1Database>();

const app = defineApp([...]);
const originalFetch = app.fetch;
app.fetch = async (request, env, cf) => {
    return dbStorage.run(env.DB, () => originalFetch.call(app, request, env, cf));
};

export default app;
```

